Two eThekwini Metro Police officers are due back at the Chatsworth Magistrate’s Court in January, to face corruption charges. Constable Jerome Govender, 33, and Constable Themba Mbhele, 34, were released on R1 500 bail each following their appearance in court on 26 November. Captain Nqobile Gwala, KwaZulu-Natal police spokesperson, said that the constables are due back to line at the Chatsworth Magistrate’s Court 13 January 2021. Govender and Mbhele were arrested for extorting money out of three victims in the Chatsworth area, in September. Gwala said: “It is alleged that on 19 September, the accused were on duty in Chatsworth when they stopped three men and requested money indicating that they have violated Covid-19 regulations. They demanded an amount ranging from R500 to R1000 and those who failed to pay were placed in the back of the van until money was paid.” The victims reported the incident to Chatsworth police and a case of corruption was opened for investigation. “The docket was transferred to Provincial Anti-corruption Unit for further investigation. The pair were arrested on 26 November, in Chatsworth,” Gwala added. The arrest of the officers was welcomed by the provincial commissioner,  Lieutenant General Khombinkosi Jula. He said: “This arrest proves that no one is above the law.”